description: From Abenaki waniigan (“pit trap, container for sundries”); liken klahigan (“wooden trap”), Ojibwe waanikaan (“pit, excavated hole”).

entries.meaning: (US, Maine, lumber trade) A boat for conveying provisions, tools, and so forth.
(US, Maine, lumber trade) Any location or cache of equipment, such as a camp, building, or chest of supplies or tools.
(US, Maine, lumber trade) The company store debt of a lumberman.
